Red Red Wine by Laura Yoshizawa

Data Source

This is a data analysis of red wine samples, captured by Paulo Cortez, Antonio Cerdeira, Fernando Almeida, Telmo Matos and Jose Reis. Red Wines were analyzed on their physical qualities (chlorides, pH, alcohol by volume, etc…), and subjectively measured by wine experts.

Univariate Analysis

Dataset Structure

This dataset is composed of 1599 red wines with 12 features: fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, density, pH, sulphates, alcohol, and quality. With the exception of quality, all of the features reflect the chemical composition of the wine, and the values are stored numerically. The quality variable was determined subjectively by a panel of three wine experts, with the median score being taken. This value is stored as an integer.

There is a variable named ‘X’, which is an index number for the wine. This variable has been removed from the dataset.

Main Features

The main feature of interest within the dataset is the quality. This is because it is the only subjective variable, and is determined by the aroma and taste of the wine. The other features are properties that alter the smell and taste, which can affect the quality grade.

Supporting Features

I think that the acidity values (fixed, volatile, and citric) and the sulfur values (free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, and sulphates) will support my investigation into the quality the most since those will impact the smell and taste of the wines the most.

New Variables

The total.acid variable was created which is the sum of fixed acid, volatile acid, and citric acid. This is because I want to know if any particular acid affects the quality of the wine, or if it is the total amount of acid within the wine, regardless of type.

Plot Adjustments

A univariate examination was conducted on all features, and no operations were performed to adjust the data. This is because I wanted to see whe whole set of data, including the outliers, since the irregularities could contribute to the overall quality of the wine.

Bivariate Plots Section

From the correlation plot above, a few things stand out. The negative correlation between the acids and pH makes sense, because more acid will result in a lower pH. The positve correlation between free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide also makes sense, because free sulfur dioxide is a component of total sulfur dioxide.

Bivariate Analysis

Relationships with Quality

The quality of the wine was correlated the most with alcohol content at 0.48.
As the alcohol content increased in the wine, the quality increased as well. The average alcohol content of the worst rated wines was 9.955%, and the average alcohol content of the hgiehst rating wines was 12.09%.

Volatile acidity had an inverse correlation with quality, -0.39, with the lowest quality wines having a volatile acidity average of .8845. The highest quality wines had a volatile acidity of .4233. This relationship is expected, as volatile acid is defined as “the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste.”

Citric Acid has a small correlation with quality, with a correlation coefficient of 0.23. The median value for the worst quality wines was 0.035, and the median value for the highest quality wines was 0.42. This relationship is expected, as citric acid is described as “found in small quantities, citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines.”

Sulphates also has a small positvie correlation with quality, with a correlation coefficient of 0.25. The median value for the worst quality wines was 0.5450, and the median value for the highest quality wines was 0.74. Sulphates are described as “a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant.”

Interesting Relationships

I thought it was interesting how Citric Acid and Volatile Acidity are inversely correlated. In addition to the correlation between Citric Acid and Quality and Volatile Acidity and Quality, I also looked at the ratio of Citric Acid and Volatile Acidity to Quality. Because increasing Citric Acid was correlated to an increase in Quality, but an increase in Volatile Acidity was negatively correlated to Quality, I was curious if a higher Citric Acid to Volatile Acidity ratio was correlated with an increase in quality.

The majority of wines in the dataset have more volatile acidity than citric acid, but as the ratio increases, the quality goes up. The mean and median wines for the highest quality ratings (7 and 8), have a ratio greater than 1.

Strongest Correlations

  • -0.68 fixed acidity and pH
  • 0.67 fixed acidity and citric acid
  • 0.67 fixed acidity and density
  • 0.67 free sulfur dioxide and total sulfur dioxide

Because free sulfur dioxide is included in total sulfur dioxide, this strong relationship is expected.

Multivariate Plots Section

Here’s another comparison of citric acid to volatile acidity, colored by quality.

As fixed acidity increases, density increases as well. It also appears that quality is impacted by this relationship, as the least dense wines within a specific level of fixed acidity are given higher quality ratings.

The previous analysis pointed out an interesting correlation between fixed acidity and pH, and density. Here these three features are plotted together. As fixed acidity increases, pH decreases, and density increases.

Here we look at how citric acid and alcohol are related to quality. As quality increases, the alcohol content increases. Higher quality wines also appear to have a higher amount of citric acid, however a wide range of citric acid is used in wines with a quality of 5 or 6. It also appears that as alcohol content increases, the amount of citric acid increases as well.

This plot looks at free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, and the levels of residual sugar. Free sulfur dioxide is a component of total sulfur dioxide, and the positive correlation is apparent. When colored by residual sugar, it appears that the wines with higher amounts of residual sugar contain more total sulfur dioxide and free sulfur dioxide.

Multivariate Analysis

Relationships with Quality In the Bivariate analysis, I explored the relationship between citric acid and volatile acid and how they impact quality. In this multivariate analysis, I explored this even further.

The highest quality wines not only have a higher citric acid to volatile acidity ratio, but also a lower density to fixed acidity ratio as well.

Additionally, while citric acid and alcohol content within the wines did not appear to have any correlation, it became apparent that citric acid and alcohol are both significant factors when comparing between quality. On the last chart, it shows that higher quality wines not noly have the higher alcohol content, but higher amounts of citric acid as well.

Other Relationships From the bivariate analysis, the fixed acidity had a strong correlation coefficient with pH, citric acid, and density, so I looked into these relationships a bit more.

As fixed acidity increased, pH decreased and citric acid increased. When faceted by quality, it didn’t appear that the fixed acidity and pH had any substantial influence on the quality. This is further substantiated by the correlation grid from the Bivariate analysis.

Final Plots and Summary

Alcohol by Quality

Plot One looks at the relationship between Alcohol by Volume and Quality. As alcohol content was the factor that had the strongest correlation with quality, this plot shows the kernel density of alcohol volume, colored by quality. As you can see in the plot, the lowest quality wines have the highest kernel density under 11% Alcohol by Volume, while the highest quality wines have the highest kernel density over 11%. This shows a trend that more high quality wines have higher amounts of alcohol.

Fixed Acidity and Density

This plot looks at the relationship of Density and Fixed Acidity, and colors it by quality. Fixed acidity and density have a positive correlation, and when looking at the wine quality on the plot, an interesting observation is made: while the the trendlines for each quality level appears to have roughly the same slope, the y-intercept decreases with quality. This means that higher quality wines are less dense when compared to other wines with the same amounts of fixed acidity.

Impact of Citric Acid and Volatile Acidity on Quality

This plot looks at the ratio of Citric Acid and Volatile Acidity and compares them by quality. the mean and median ratios are plotted on the above table in red and orange respectively. This diagram shows that as the ratio increases, the quality of the wine increases as well. In fact, of the top quality wines, rated 7 and 8, the mean and median wines have a ratio greater than 1. This means higher quality wines contain more citric acid than volatile acidity.

Reflection

This red wine dataset contains information on 1599 different wines, with 11 physical features and 1 subjective feature. This subjective feature is quality, and was determined by a panel of three wine experts. To explore this dataset, one question stood out: What determines the quality of each wine?

From the initial examination of data, I thought that acids, sulfurs, and sulphates would be the biggest contributor towards wine quality. However the feature that correlated the highest with quality was neither of them: it was alcohol content. While larger amounts of alcohol doesn’t cause higher quality, wines with larger alcohol by volume amounts tended to be rated higher by the wine experts.

Citric acid and volatile acidity also were correlated with the quality of the wines as well: Citric acid had a positive correlation, while volatile acid had a negative correlation. Their inverse relationship with quality interested me, so I not only investigated the relationship between the two acids, but the ratio of the two when compared to quality as well. This lead to the observation that wines with a higher citric acid to volatile acidity ratio tend to have a higher quality.

Another interesting observation from the dataset is how fixed acidity has a strong correlation with pH and citric acid. Hoewver when a plot was faceted by quality, it didn’t appear that fixed acidity had a correlation with quality.
But when fixed acidity was plotted with density, it appears that higher quality wines have lower densities compared to other wines with the same amount of fixed acidity.

Because this dataset is mostly composed of the chemical composition of these wines, there are a lot of limitations on this analysis. The length of fermentation, types of grapes used, type of container the wine was fermented in (wood or plastic? what type of wood?), and other additives contribute to the quality of wine, but were not included in the dataset. Additionally, it would be interesting to know the year of some wines, to see if the wines maintain the same chemical properties every year, or what values change.
